Ich hab meine Masterarbeit im Bereich der Bioanorganik angefertigt. Dafür habe ich die Theorie eines Physikers und die Erkenntnisse von Biologen verwendet, aber niemand außer einem Chemiker hätte diese Arbeit leisten können.

Glauben Leute, ein Chemiestudium bestünde nur aus dem lesen abgestumpfter Physik- und Biobücher?
Leute, wir entwickeln eigene Theorien, Modelle und wissenschaftliche Herangehensweisen. 
Ja, die Chemie liegt iwie zwischen Physik und Bio, aber genau das ist ihre Stärke.

And I'm well aware that chemists should learn chemical reactions, but I'd also argue that exams should actually try to align with the lecture's core message. 
I have a lot of other stories about poorly designed exams, but suffice to say that I prefer other forms of testing.

We had a lecture where the goal was learning about how industry processes changed to more renewable systems and it was super interesting. Yet, what was asked in the final wasn't explaining what changed but reproduction of pretty much every chemical equation shown in the lecture.

Over the past five years of binge learning and horribly designed exams, I can safely say that exams can easily be the worst way of probing someone's progress in a subject.
Especially the ones designed completely parallel to the messages of the lecture.

If all goes well, I'll have taken and passed the last exam of my life. 
After I had to write 20 exams in my master program, 16 more than I'd have written in my original universitie's master program, it's hard to express how relieving that feels.

Too many people think science is free from cultural bias just because some models involve pretty numbers and formulas.

I think that is what bothered me a long time with chemistry. The way how the chemical industry has such a large influence in academic research so that many goals in academia are based on industrial needs. Knowledge kinda becomes tainted when it's gained to make money off of it.

Or maybe disqualifies a lot of what chemists do as real, unadulterated science, idk. 
This is not exclusive to chemistry as a science, but chemistry has a unique connection to this in the way that it has become a big part of the feel chemistry has to it.

cool particle interactions or weird squid, chemists are viewed a bit more like engineers. Not solely as people describing reactions, but also as people tinkering with new reactions so that the industry can use it. 
The attachment of industry to chemistry alters it as a science.

BC there is a certain branch of science that doesn't just do stuff and write it down to gain knowledge. It also has an intent behind it. 
Where (in very broad strokes) physicists and biologists are viewed by society as people that want to gather knowledge about

I really want to talk about how chemistry  and every scientific field related to it or material science is an outlier to the general notion of science as a descriptive device to just understand our world.

Imagine tinkering with an energy source denser than anything on this planet and using not so much as basic safety measures. 
A lump of metal that can incinerate cities, but what could go wrong.

instead of an array of safety blocks. 
He supposedly did the expirement this way dozens of times. 
Needless to say, the screw driver slipped at one point. Blue light, heat wave. 
He died a few weeks later.

He tried a similar thing with two mirror half spheres instead of cubes. They were aimed to initiate the chain reaction when completely engulfing the core. 
He disregarded Richard Feynman's advice to pursue his goal in a safer way and only left a screen driver between both spheres

He is the person that is said to have received the highest dose of nuclear radiation. ever. 

A colleague of his sat next to him while he was dying. He was to suffer the same fate a few years later.

A lot, as it turns out. One guy tried to reach the point right before the chain reaction started with metal alloy cubes placed around the core. He dropped one too many by accident, resulting in a blue light and a heat wave. 
The researcher died 20 days or so later.

The idea was that you could initiate the chain reaction by reflecting the neutrons the plutonium ball emitted back to it with mirrors. 
The researchers started out careful but as it is with routine, you start to get less and less careful over time. 
"what could go wrong"

So this "demon core" was a ball of plutonium that was at critical mass. That is a point where the atoms inside of the ball can start a nuclear chain reaction with an initiation. Resulting in a blast of radiation that should in the end lead to a field test of a new fission bomb.

learnt more about the demon core and the research attached to it and it's such a thrilling story of human hubris. 

Imagine trying to control a ball of critical Plutonium without so much as safety equipment.

and it's not like it's going to be worth it.  
The industrial job market is over saturated and academic research is just so unattractive to me. 

Will I at least start my phd? Yes.
But I don't think that I will go either route after that. 

I want to teach stuff to people.

It used to be fun. Fun people, fun internships, fun topics. Stressful and strenuous, yes, but the study returned something. 
I don't have fun anymore, though. It's just anxiety that I'm not good enough for any of this.

The mediocre to bad job chances and possible prestige of doing a phd just don't seem to justify the working hours, the pressure and most of all, the time required to finish a phd. 

I'm 23 and I already feel burnt out most of the time.

October of this year, I will have studied chemistry for five years and will be close to have achieved a Master's Degree and starting my phd.
And the closer I get to the degree I once wanted so badly, the more I doubt that its worth it.
